'''Uneotsutamoto Shrine''' (うねおつたもとじんじゃ) is a shrine in {{ill|lt=Kashihara|Q496319|WD=Q496319|1=Kashihara, Nara}}, {{ill|lt=Nara Prefecture|Q131287|WD=Q131287|1=Nara Prefecture}}. It is located on the northwestern foot of {{ill|lt=Mount Amanokagu|Q11443780|WD=Q11443780|1=Mount Amanokagu}}, and to the adjacent northeast stands another Shikinaisha, {{ill|lt=Uneo ni Imasu Taketsuchi-yasu Shrine|Q30931377|WD=Q30931377|1=Uneoza Taketsuyasugami Shrine}}. It is also called "Nakisawa Shrine" (written with characters such as 啼澤, 哭沢, 泣沢) and is known as "Nakisawa no Mori."
{{右|[[画像:畝尾都多本神社 - DGYD2GRV0AIIJd6.jpg|none|thumb|250px|Haiden]]}}
{{右|[[画像:畝尾都多本神社 - DGYEGSoVwAE5PVn.jpg|none|thumb|250px|Sacred well (shintai)]]}}

=== Enshrined deity ===
*{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Nakisawa-me-no-Kami|1=UNKNOWN}} (なきさわめのかみ)
There is a well called Nakisawa, and that well is worshiped as the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=shintai|1=UNKNOWN}}<ref>{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}} Jinmyōchō</ref>.

=== History ===
The founding is unknown, but in Book 2, poem 202 of the '{{ill|lt=Man'yōshū|Q834321|WD=Q834321|1=Man'yōshū}}':
:Though sacred sake is offered and prayers made at Nakisawa Shrine, my jewel child does not know the high sun.
:(Even though sacred sake is offered to the goddess of Nakisawa Shrine and prayers are made to prolong the life of the deceased prince, the prince has finally gone to rule the heavens.)
The left-side note records:
:"This one poem, according to {{ill|lt=Ruijū Karin|Q11665187|WD=Q11665187|1=Ruijū Karin}}, is said to be a song by {{ill|lt=Hinokuma no Ōkimi|Q30932401|WD=Q30932401|1=Hinokuma no Ōkimi}} lamenting {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Nakisawa-me-no-Kami|1=UNKNOWN}}<ref>{{ill|lt=Kojiki|Q813031|WD=Q813031|1=Kojiki}}</ref>. Looking at the Nihongi: in autumn, seventh month, on the day Kōjutsu, in the 10th year (696), later prince no mikoto passed away."
This is a waka of resentment toward Nakisawa-me-no-Kami: in {{ill|lt=696|Q23486|WD=Q23486|lt=Jitō Tennō 10 (696)|1=696}}, Matsukuma no Ōkimi offered sacred sake to a revival deity and prayed for {{ill|lt=Prince Takechi|Q837590|WD=Q837590|1=Prince Takechi}}'s life, but he did not return to life<ref>{{ill|lt=Man'yōshū|Q834321|WD=Q834321|1=Man'yōshū}}</ref><ref>[http://www.city.kashihara.nara.jp/kankou/own_kankou/kankou/spot/uneotsutamoto.html Kashihara City / Uneotsutamoto Shrine]</ref>. From this, Uneotsutamoto Shrine is thought to have already existed in the {{ill|lt=Asuka period|Q210688|WD=Q210688|1=Asuka period}}. On a precinct stone monument, in addition to the above Man'yōshū annotation, are engraved a passage from {{ill|lt=Hirata Atsutane|Q2572749|WD=Q2572749|1=Hirata Atsutane}}'s 'Tamasuki' saying "Nakisawa-me deity is a deity for life-begging," and a quotation from {{ill|lt=Motoori Norinaga|Q384647|WD=Q384647|1=Motoori Norinaga}}'s '{{ill|lt=Kojikiden|Q11410835|WD=Q11410835|1=Kojiki-den}}' saying "etymologically, sawa-me connects to rain and is a water deity"<ref>[http://engishiki.org/yamato/html/031410-01.html Uneotsutamoto Shrine - Investigation of Engishiki shrines]</ref>.

In the 1446 (Bun'an 3) 'Washū Gokōri Jinja Jinmyōchō Tairyaku Chūkai,' together with {{ill|lt=Amanokagu-yama Shrine|Q98082987|WD=Q98082987|lt=Amanokagu ni Imasu Kushimakoto Shrine|1=Amanokaguyama Shrine}}, Sakamon Shrine (Ame-no-Iwato Shrine), and {{ill|lt=Uneo ni Imasu Taketsuchi-yasu Shrine|Q30931377|WD=Q30931377|1=Uneoza Taketsuyasugami Shrine}}, it is referred to as "Amanokagu-yama ni Imasu Yotsudokoro Shrines"<ref>[https://genbu.net/data/yamato/tutamoto_title.htm Uneotsutamoto Shrine]</ref>.

It is identified with Uneotsutamoto Shrine in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|lt=Engishiki-listed shrine|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} and stands adjacent to the also-listed {{ill|lt=Uneo ni Imasu Taketsuchi-yasu Shrine|Q30931377|WD=Q30931377|1=Uneoza Taketsuyasugami Shrine}}. Remains of the "Kaguyama Shōsō," an office that stored and managed {{ill|lt=shōzei|Q11545591|WD=Q11545591|1=shōzei}} in the {{ill|lt=Nara period|Q189178|WD=Q189178|1=Nara period}}, have been excavated nearby.

The shrine buildings were rebuilt in the {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} era.

=== Name origin ===
"Une" means a wavy/ridged place. "O" means where a mountain foot stretches long like an animal tail. "Uneo" thus means mountain foot; this refers to the foot of Mount Kagu.
